    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-11-19T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-11-19T09:00:00-05:00" n="224"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d224">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6831/45: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-11-19T16:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 19, 1924—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. When I carried out the instructions contained in your number 81 November 10,
                    6 p.m.<note n="19" xml:id="d224fn19">“81. Department’s 80, November 8, 3 P.M.
                        Please informally give to the Foreign Office a copy of the text of
                        Department’s note to the Charge d’Affaires of Greece, replying to his note
                        No. 934 of September 10, as well as the text of the draft note proposed for
                        exchange. Hughes.” (File no. 611.6831/43.)</note> Snipesos [<hi
                        rend="italic">Roussos</hi>] said that the Greek Government had decided to
                    apply minimum tariff rates for three months after December 10 pending conclusion
                    of new treaty and that this time might be extended if negotiations were not then
                    concluded. He said he had already telegraphed Greek Legation to communicate this
                    to you.</p>
                <p>On looking over your proposed draft he added that it seemed to him to follow the
                    lines acceptable to his Government and that he would hasten the consultations
                    necessary for acting upon it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
